<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>TYPOSQUATTING AND DEPENDENCY CONFUSION</title>

  <critical>Package typosquatting and dependency confusion are supply chain attacks where malicious packages masquerade as legitimate ones. A single typo in package.json or requirements.txt can lead to RCE. Organizations with internal packages are especially vulnerable to namespace confusion attacks.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Package typosquatting detection
    - Dependency confusion attacks
    - Namespace hijacking
    - Package manifest analysis
    - Internal package security
    - Registry security assessment
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. TYPOSQUATTING IDENTIFICATION
       {% raw %}
       # Common typosquatting patterns:
       # - lodash → lodahs, lodsh, lodash-utils
       # - requests → requets, request, reqeusts
       # - numpy → nunpy, numpi, numpy-utils

       # Generation techniques:
       # - Character substitution: requests → requezts
       # - Character omission: requests → reqests
       # - Character addition: requests → requestss
       # - Character transposition: requests → reqeusts
       # - Homograph: requests → rеquests (Cyrillic е)
       # - Delimiter change: lodash → lo-dash, lo_dash

       # Tools for detection
       # pip-audit, npm audit, safety, snyk

       # Check installed packages
       pip list | xargs -I {} pip show {} | grep -E "^(Name|Author|Home-page)"
       npm list --depth=0
       {% endraw %}

    2. DEPENDENCY CONFUSION ATTACK
       {% raw %}
       # Dependency confusion exploits package resolution

       # Scenario:
       # - Company has internal package "company-utils"
       # - Only exists on internal registry
       # - Attacker publishes "company-utils" to npm/PyPI
       # - Build system pulls public version

       # Finding internal package names:
       # - GitHub search: "company-" filename:package.json
       # - NPM scope typos: @compny/utils vs @company/utils
       # - Leaked package.json in JS bundles
       # - Error messages revealing package names

       # Attack execution:
       # 1. Find internal package name
       # 2. Register on public registry
       # 3. Use higher version number
       # 4. Add postinstall script with payload
       {% endraw %}

    3. MANIFEST ANALYSIS
       {% raw %}
       # Analyze package.json
       cat package.json | jq '.dependencies, .devDependencies'

       # Check for risky patterns
       # - No version pinning: "lodash": "*"
       # - Git dependencies: "git://github.com/..."
       # - Local paths: "file:../internal-pkg"
       # - Pre-release versions: "^1.0.0-alpha"

       # Python requirements analysis
       cat requirements.txt
       # Look for:
       # - Missing version constraints
       # - --extra-index-url (dependency confusion risk)
       # - -f or --find-links to external URLs

       # Ruby Gemfile analysis
       # Check for github: sources
       # Check for git: sources without ref
       {% endraw %}

    4. NAMESPACE HIJACKING
       {% raw %}
       # Check for available namespaces

       # npm scopes
       npm view @company/utils  # 404 = available
       npm view @companyy/utils # typosquat potential

       # PyPI availability
       pip download company-utils  # Check if exists

       # Go modules
       go get github.com/company/utils  # Repo takeover possible

       # Docker Hub
       docker pull company/utils  # Namespace available?

       # Org abandonment
       # Check if GitHub org still exists
       # Expired domains for git:// URLs
       {% endraw %}

    5. POSTINSTALL SCRIPT ANALYSIS
       {% raw %}
       # npm packages can run scripts on install

       # Check for install scripts
       cat package.json | jq '.scripts | {preinstall, install, postinstall}'

       # Python setup.py can run arbitrary code
       python setup.py --help-commands
       # setup.py runs during: pip install

       # Suspicious patterns:
       # - Network requests during install
       # - Environment variable exfiltration
       # - Reverse shells
       # - File system access outside package

       # Analyze script contents
       # Look for: eval, exec, curl, wget, nc
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <version_number_attack>
      {% raw %}
      # Higher version numbers take precedence

      # If internal package is 1.0.0
      # Publish malicious 99999.0.0 to public registry
      # Build system chooses higher version

      # Bypass version pinning
      # Exact pin: "internal-pkg": "1.0.0"
      # Attack: Wait for version bump, publish 1.0.1 first

      # Pre-release exploitation
      # "pkg": "^1.0.0" accepts 1.0.1-malicious
      # Some resolvers prefer pre-release
      {% endraw %}
    </version_number_attack>

    <homograph_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # Unicode lookalike characters

      # Examples:
      # requests vs rеquests (Cyrillic е: U+0435)
      # lodash vs lоdash (Cyrillic о: U+043E)
      # numpy vs numру (Cyrillic у: U+0443)

      # Detection:
      # - Non-ASCII character detection
      # - Punycode/IDN in package names
      # - Visual inspection may miss these

      # Some registries block homographs
      # But not all check thoroughly
      {% endraw %}
    </homograph_attacks>

    <abandoned_package_takeover>
      {% raw %}
      # Find abandoned but popular packages

      # Indicators:
      # - No commits in years
      # - Maintainer email domain expired
      # - GitHub repo deleted/renamed

      # Takeover vectors:
      # - Claim expired maintainer domain
      # - npm package ownership transfer
      # - GitHub repo rename + recreation

      # Check package metadata
      npm view <package> maintainers
      pip show <package> | grep Author-email
      {% endraw %}
    </abandoned_package_takeover>

    <proxy_registry_attacks>
      {% raw %}
      # Proxy registries cache packages
      # Can be poisoned or bypassed

      # Artifactory/Nexus confusion
      # Virtual repository ordering matters
      # If public comes before private = vulnerable

      # Cache poisoning
      # If proxy caches malicious package
      # All builds get malicious version

       # Check proxy configuration
       # npm: .npmrc with registry
       # pip: pip.conf with index-url
       # Maven: settings.xml repositories
      {% endraw %}
    </proxy_registry_attacks>

    <lockfile_manipulation>
      {% raw %}
      # Lockfiles can be manipulated in PRs

      # package-lock.json tampering
      # - Change integrity hashes
      # - Modify resolved URLs
      # - Point to malicious registries

      # yarn.lock manipulation
      # Different resolution algorithm
      # Can add unexpected dependencies

      # Lockfile review is often skipped
      # Diff is hard to read
      # Auto-merge of lockfile updates
      {% endraw %}
    </lockfile_manipulation>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor package installations for typos
    - Alert on new dependencies from public registries
    - Compare package names against known-good list
    - Check for postinstall scripts in dependencies
    - Audit .npmrc and pip.conf configurations
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Identify typosquatting opportunities
    - Find internal package names
    - Check registry configuration vulnerabilities
    - Analyze dependency resolution order
    - Test package installation security
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Always use scoped packages for internal code (@company/pkg)
    - Pin exact versions in production (=1.0.0 not ^1.0.0)
    - Configure registries to block public packages with internal names
    - Review postinstall scripts before npm install
    - Use --ignore-scripts for untrusted packages
    - Check lockfile diffs carefully in PRs
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Supply chain attacks are devastatingly effective because developers inherently trust packages. A single typo in a dependency name can compromise every system that builds the project. Internal package names are especially valuable - if you find them, check if they're claimable on public registries. Always recommend scoped namespaces and strict registry configurations.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
